      <li>
         <title>Student Office Hours</title>

          <p>
            Fridays 10:30 a.m. - 12:20 p.m. and by appointment, May 327 and Zoom
          </p>
          <p>I’ve set aside this time specifically for you: to answer your questions, discuss your ideas, and talk about any aspect of class, writing, or your college/career plans. My office hours can be either virtual or in person on Mondays and Wednesdays, 11:30 a.m.–12:20 p.m. You may schedule a time on Starfish (login required) or just drop in. I can also meet with you other times by appointment, either virtually or in person. </p>
<p>While I encourage you to meet with me in person in May 327, I also offer virtual office hours. These Zoom meetings [https://tinyurl.com/CoyneZoomOfficeHours] can be with or without video, but please be sure your name is clearly displayed. On Zoom, I’ll have a waiting room enabled in case multiple students join at the same time. You can also access the Zoom link on Canvas and Starfish. </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <title>Class Meetings</title>
      </li>
        <p>
          Tuesdays 10:30 a.m. - 12:20 p.m. in May XXX
        </p>
      <li>
        <title>Course Description</title>

        <p>
        From the catalog: “A career-oriented course introducing students to a wide variety of writing formats used in business, government, and the professions. Assignments include resumes and other employment documents, letters and memos, reports, and presentations. This course emphasizes drafting, critiquing, rewriting, and editing, as well as collaborative writing and presentation skills. Prerequisite: ENWR 110 Composition II or permission of the instructor.” 
  
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <title>Textbook &amp; Materials </title>

        <p>
          There is no required textbook to purchase for this course. Instead, you’ll find a selection of readings from open educational resources (OERs) and other content on Canvas. You’ll also watch recorded presentations through Canvas, in which I cover both material from our readings and additional important information about professional writing. These recordings are part of the asynchronous aspect of our course.         </p>      
        </li>
    </dl>
